<p>According to <strong><a href="https://www.atlassian.com/agile/scrum/sprints">Atlassian</a></strong>:</p>
<p><span>~ A <strong>sprint</strong> is a short, time-boxed period when a scrum team works to complete a set amount of work.</span></p>
<p><strong>Sprint #4</strong> of <strong><a href="https://www.meetup.com/bostonphp/events/283821265/">The Working Group</a></strong> began April 1, 2022 and ends April 15, 2022. What set amount of work you choose to accomplish in your job search during this sprint is your decision.</p>
<p>According to <strong><a href="https://stackoverflow.blog/2022/03/17/new-data-what-makes-developers-happy-at-work/">Stack Overflow</a></strong>:</p>
<p>~ Nearly 80% of developers <strong>ARE NOT</strong> actively looking for a new job<span>.</span></p>
<p><span>If you signed up for <strong><a href="https://www.meetup.com/bostonphp/events/283821265/">The Working Group</a></strong> and your <strong>ARE NOT</strong> actively looking for a new job, then no further action is required on your part.</span></p>
<p><span>If, on the other hand, your are one of the estimated 565 Boston PHP members who is actively looking for a new opportunity, then review <strong><a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2020/12/23/7-simple-questions-to-help-form-your-2021-career-goals.html">7 simple questions to help form your 2021 (now 2022) career goals</a></strong>, and <strong><a href="https://www.meetup.com/bostonphp/messages/boards/thread/53491175">Introduce Yourself</a></strong> with comments about your career goals and job search strategy for the current sprint.</span></p>
